# Architecture

## Structure
- Domain-oriented: `features/dom`, `features/classification`, `features/insights`, `features/ml`, `features/feedback`, `features/sentry`, `features/editor`
- Within a feature: public entry files at the leaf name (e.g. `classifyIncident.ts`), shared `data/` for constants and rule tables, `internal/` or `*.helpers.ts` for non-exported logic used only in that feature
- `shared/types` for project-level types, `shared/utils` for small reusable helpers
- `components/` for pure UI; subfolders such as `components/sidebar/` for composite UI
- `contents/` for Plasmo CSUI entrypoints and thin wiring

## Boundaries
- `features/dom`: DOM reading, extraction, normalization only. No classification. No React.
- `features/classification`: Pure rule-based functions. No DOM access. No React.
- `features/insights`: Summary, hypothesis, priority, useful-frame, recommendations. Pure functions. No DOM. No React.
- `features/ml`: Feature extraction, inference, TF model, retrain. No React.
- `features/feedback`: Storage and adaptive similarity. No React except via callers.
- `features/sentry`: Page analysis orchestration (`analyzeCurrentPage`). No React.
- `features/editor`: Open-in-editor helpers. No React.
- `components/`: Pure UI. No business logic.

## Code Style
- No `any` — use `unknown` + narrowing when needed
- Pure functions wherever possible
- No business logic inside React components
- Files should stay under ~200 lines
- No premature generic abstractions — build concretely first
- No dead files or placeholder architecture without implementation
- Do not add comments in source (TypeScript, TSX, CSS); keep code self-explanatory
